Subject: [PATCH] =?UTF-8?q?Workout=20screen=20redesign=20=E2=80=94=20Phase?=
 =?UTF-8?q?=202:=20colour,=20iconography,=20scaffold=20consistency?=
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

- Add a dedicated --intensity (amber) token for the interval timer's WORK
  phase, replacing --destructive (red) — that token already means
  delete/cancel/error everywhere else in the app, so an intense-but-fine
  work phase shouldn't borrow it. Same 'own token, not a repurposed chart
  colour' pattern already established by --pr-gold.
- Give 'Previous Workout' its own bg-muted treatment instead of the same
  bg-secondary/50 the editable stepper track and interval config panel
  use, so a read-only reference no longer visually blends with editable
  controls.
- Add set / Add exercise now share the same lucide Plus icon (previously
  a hand-typed '+' vs an icon component). Deliberately kept Add Set's
  tinted style distinct from Add Exercise's solid Button — they're
  different-weight actions (many-per-exercise vs occasional/structural),
  so making them pixel-identical would erase a real hierarchy distinction
  rather than fix an accidental one.
- Unilateral set rows: hoisted the per-side Kg/Reps/Sec column labels
  into a single header shown once per set (matching the pattern the
  standard/bilateral row already used), removing 2x label repetition
  across Left/Right. Switched the row to a 3-column grid so the header
  and each side's fields share real column alignment.

Scope note: UnilateralSetInputs is also rendered by the History edit
screen, not just the Workout screen — the header-hoist change is shared
code, so History's unilateral edit rows inherit the same decluttering
as a side effect. Purely presentational (no field/behavior changes), so
this should only be a net improvement there, not a regression.

Deferred from the plan, explicitly not implemented in this pass: a
persistent (not just celebratory) per-set 'beats previous' indicator
using --pr-gold. That requires new comparison logic (which of last
session's sets to compare each current set against), which is a
behavior/logic addition beyond a visual redesign pass and wasn't
reviewed — flagging as a candidate for a dedicated follow-up rather
than folding it in unreviewed.

Verified via tsc/eslint against a clean main baseline — no new errors
introduced.
